    "narrative": "The cornerstone of today\u2019s lineup is **Corbin Carroll**, who registers as an elite play with a massive 87.14 score against Painter. While the base projection is strong, the combination of a favorable SP skill matchup (+19%) and his elite speed profile against a pitcher susceptible to the running game makes him our primary catalyst for stolen bases, which remain our scarcest commodity. Joining him as a high-upside play is **Mickey Moniak** (65.00), who benefits from a significant dynamic platoon advantage (+14%) and favorable wind conditions that help offset the modest SP skill rating of Pivetta. Similarly, **Brice Turang** earns a strong recommendation (67.58) by leveraging his leadoff spot (+10% order bonus) and a positive matchup against Littell to anchor our daily efficiency.\n\nThe most difficult decision on today's bench involves **Seiya Suzuki** (49.75), who narrowly missed the cut. Despite his strong base projection and favorable wind conditions, the optimizer ultimately favored the higher-floor efficiency of our starters like **Giancarlo Stanton** and **Tyler Soderstrom**. **Seiya Suzuki** simply didn't provide enough categorical separation to dislodge the current outfield configuration. Meanwhile, caution is advised regarding **James Wood** (51.65); while his speed upside against the slow delivery of Woodruff is tantalizing, the 2.90 xERA of the opposing starter introduces enough risk that he remains a lower-tier start. Because our lineup remains largely \"Lineup Pending,\" we are monitoring confirmed spots for **Josh Naylor**, **Jazz Chisholm Jr.**, **Austin Riley**, **Vinnie Pasquantino**, and others to ensure the assumed batting order bonuses hold true. We have ample depth on the bench with **Zach McKinstry**, **Max Muncy**, and **Jose Caballero**, but the current metrics suggest we are maximizing our daily scoring potential without dipping into those reserves.",
